courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) handle different set of data, provided with sophisticated and analytical findings;
2) handle SPSS in managing quantitative analysis;
3) identify and review critically the methodologies used in daily lives, media and social research;
4) identify the strengths and weaknesses of each analytical methods;
5) design and conduct sophisticated researches for their graduation project.

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to Methodology in Social Scientific Research;
2) Basic skills in conducting literature reviews: reviewing, classifying reading materials, analyzing and organizing ideas

3) How to cite references;
4) Basic statistics: Means, Normal Distribution and Standard Deviations;
5) Simple Regression Models: analyses and interpretations;
6) Usage of SPSS;
7) Qualitative researches and Methodology;
8) Basic Internet research methods

courses.required_readings:
1) Alan Bryman, Social Research Methods, 4th edition, (Oxon: Oxford University Press, 2012);
2) John W. Creswell, Research Design: Qualitative, Quantitative, and Mixed Methods Approaches, 3rd edition, (London: SAGE Publications, 2009);
3) Andy Field, Discovering Statistics Using IBM SPSS Statistics, 4th edition, (London: SAGE Publications, 2013).

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Jill Jenson, Lydia Matheson & Fiona M. Lacey, Doing Your Literature Review: Traditional and Systematic Techniques, (London: SAGE Publications, 2011);
2) Gary King, Robert O. Keohane & Sidney Verba, Designing Social Enquiry: Scientific Inference in Qualitative Research, (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1994);
3) James H. Stock & Mark M. Watson, Introduction to Econometrics, 3rd edition, (Essex: Pearson Education, 2012); 4) Peter Burnham, et al, Research Methods in Politics, 2nd edition, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2008).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) learn the on-site data-collection skills and techniques for fieldwork study;
2) explore and develop his/her own research interests;
3) work in a team and enhance the team-work spirits;
4) present his/her own idea through verbal and written presentations

By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the development of some key nation-states;
2) locate different nation-states on the map;
3) identify various political and economic institutions exercised in different nations;
4) realize a number of global and regional agendas;
5) speak with confidence, no matter in English or in Chinese;
6) relate concepts to contexts and assess the impact of one to other;
7) relate history to the development of contemporary world order;
8) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to Geopolitical studies: Geography and politics;
2) Introduction to Cold War History (I): the Western Hemisphere;
3) Introduction to Cold War History (II): the Eastern Hemisphere;
4) Post-Cold War International system: a brief overview;
5) Regions and the developing world: Asia, Middle-East and Africa, Latin America and the Caribbean;
6) Regions and the developed world: North America and Europe;
7) Challenges and Possibilities under Globalization

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) demonstrate a good command of academic English;
2) present his/her own idea through verbal and written presentations with confidence

By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) demonstrate a good command of English speaking skills;
2) present his/her own idea through verbal presentations with confidence

By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) grasp the key assumptions and implications of different major IR theories and historiographical concepts;
2) apply different theories under distinct contexts;
3) evaluate the merits/demerits of these theories in explaining world affairs;
4) relate the theories and perspectives with different courses;
5) enhance their skills to construct and substantiate their arguments in written essays

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction: Defining International Relations;
2) Overview of history: from Cold War to now;
3) Historiography and Globalization: Samuel Huntington, Edward Said, Francis Fukuyama and Antonio Negri;
4) Realism and its variants;
5) Liberalism and Democratic Peace;
6) Constructivism and Critical Theory;
7) Actors and Structure in the International system: Individual, State, and Globalization;
8) IR Theory and Global Economy: the North and the South;
9) IR Theory and Security: Balance of Power to Security Communities;
10) Culture and World Affairs;
11) Human Rights and International Relations;
12) Democratization;
13) International Institutions and Global Governance;
14) Globalization and the future of International Relations: End of IR Theories?

courses.required_readings:
1) Chris Brown & Kirsten Ainley, Understanding International Relations, 4th edition, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2009);
2) Peter Sutch & Juanita Elias, International Relations: The Basics, (Oxon: Routledge, 2007);
3) Daniel W. Drezner, Theories of International Politics and Zombies, (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 2011).

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Tim Dunne, Milja Kurki & Steve Smith (eds.), International Relations Theories: Discipline and Diversity, 2nd edition (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2010);
2) John Baylis, Steve Smith, & Patricia Owens (eds.), The Globalization of World Politics: an Introduction to International Relations, 5th edition, (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2010);
3) Mark Beeson & Nick Bisley (eds.), Issues in 21st century World Politics, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2010);
4) Cynthia Weber, International Relations Theory: a critical introduction, 3rd edition, (Oxon: Routledge, 2010);
5) Samuel P. Huntington, The Clash of Civilizations: and the remaking of world order, (London: Simon & Schuster, 1997);
6) Michael Hardt & Antonio Negri, Empire, (Harvard: Harvard University Press, 2000);
7) Edward W. Said, Culture and Imperialism, (London: Vintage Press, 1993);
8) Francis Fukuyama, The End of History and the Last Man, (New York, Harper Collins, 1992);
9) Karen Mingst & Ivan M. Arreguín-Toft, Essentials of International Relations, 5th edition, (New York: W.W. Norton & Company, 2010).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify different concepts enshrined by the International Law;
2) identify the usefulness and limitations of International Law in addressing challenges in terms of Global Governance;
3) identify the key role of states, non-state actors and international institutions in the international community;
4) identify the formulation of international law as a combined contribution of different actors in the World;
5) relate concepts to contexts and assess their impacts;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to Global Governance;
2) Nature and Sources of International Law;
3) Law of Treaties;
4) International Court of Justice and dispute-settlement;
5) Law of the Sea;
6) States and Sovereignty: personality, statehood, recognition and jurisdiction;
7) Responsibilities to Protect and Humanitarian Intervention;
8) United Nations and its functions;
9) Regional Organizations and Global Governance;
10) Non-State actors: Rise and Governance;
11) Bretton Woods System and the Global Financial Order;
12) Hong Kong, China, and International Law

courses.recommended_readings:
1) David Held & Anthony McGrew, Governing Globalization: Power, Authority and Global Governance, (Cambridge: Polity Press, 2003);
2) Daphné Josselin & William Wallace (eds.), Non-State Actors in World Politics, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2001);
3) Martti Koskenniemi, The Politics of International Law, (Oxford: Hart Publishing, 2011); 4) Christian Reus-Smit (ed.), The Politics of International Law, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students should be able to:

1) understand basic theory of macroeconomics and microeconomics;
2) identify different concepts pertinent to international economics;
3) read and analyze economic indicators in the daily lives;
4) understand the interconnectedness between politics and economics in the era of globalization;
5) think critically.

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Dominic Kelly & Wyn Grant (eds.), The Politics of International Trade in the 21st century: Actors, Issues and Regional Dynamics, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2005);
2) James Rickards, Currency Wars: The Making of the Next Global Crisis, (London: Portfolio, 2011);
3) Fredric S. Mishkin & Stanley Eakins, Financial Markets and Institutions, (London: Pearson Education, 2012)

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the concepts and key features of the Chinese foreign policies;
2) identify the relationship between China with other nations, notably the U.S., BRICS and its neighbours in Asia-Pacific;
3) identify the driving forces of Chinese foreign and security policies;
4) identify the changes and continuities in Chinese foreign policies;
5) assess critically the impact of different policies towards the Global Governance;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to Chinese foreign policies: a historical overview since 1949;
2) Analytical Framework in formulating foreign policies: the Party, the Bureaucrats, the think-tanks, the Military and Public Opinions;
3) Chinese national security and strategic culture: its IR view and impact on foreign policies;
4) China's conception of Sovereignty and International Order

5) Chinese foreign relations with Asia, Latin America, Africa and Middle East;
6) Chinese foreign relations with Europe and North America;
7) Relations with major powers: US, Japan and Russia;
8) China's role in Global Governance: Trade and Security;
9) China turns to Multilateralism;
10) China and the peripheries: Tibet, Xinjiang, Taiwan and Hong Kong.

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Lai Hongyi, The Domestic Sources of China's Foreign Policy: Regimes, Leadership, Priorities and Processes, (Oxon: Routledge, 2010);
2) Susan Shirk, China: Fragile Superpower, (New York: Oxford University Press, 2008);
3) Wang Gangwu & Zheng Yongnian (eds.), China and the New International Order, (Oxon: Routledge, 2008);
4) Alastair Iain Johnston, Social States: China in International Institutions, 1980-2000, (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 2008);
5) Robert G. Sutter, Chinese Foreign Relations: Power and Policy since the Cold War, 3rd edition, (Lanham: Rowman & Littlefield, 2012);
6) Guoguang Wu & Helen Lansdowne (eds.), China Turns to Multilateralism: Foreign policy and Regional Security, (Oxon: Routledge, 2008).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course student should be able to:

1) identify the differences and relations between various cultures and their respective interpretations on several agenda-items in the Global Community;
2) identify and assess critically the integrity and validity of the interpretations;
3) relate contents with their daily life examples;
4) think critically

By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the key concepts and features of the respective politico-economic-cultural systems of South Korea;
2) identify the challenges and opportunities engendered by Globalization brought to the system;
3) identify the characteristics of South Korea in terms of their attitudes and priorities towards Globalization;
4) relate the content with the daily contexts;
5) relate the content with a number of theoretical approaches from other courses;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Theoretical Discussion on the South Korean political economy;
2) Historical review of Transformation of South Korea in the 20th century;
3) Mechanisms and Institutions in foreign policy-making: public opinion, strategic culture, interest groups, governments and parties;
4) Changes of Political cultures in South Korea before and after democratization;
5) Globalization of Korean enterprises: Case of Samsung and Hyundai;
6) Hallyu from Its Origin to Present: the Role of Government

;
7) Security concerns and the Inter-Korean Relations;
8) Social changes and the rise of civil societies in South Korea;
9) Global impact of the Korean popular culture: K-Pop, Drama and Movie ;
10) South Korea and the concept of ' Middle Power';
11) Assessment over the impact of Globalization on South Korea foreign policy, society and culture

courses.required_readings:
1) Chang Yun-Shik, Hyun-Ho Seok, and Donald L. Baker (eds.) Korea confronts Globalization, (Oxon: Routledge, 2009);
2) Samuel S. Kim (ed.) Korea's globalization, (Oxford: Cambridge University Press), 2000;
3) Kim Youna (ed.) The Korean Wave: Korean Media Go Global. (London: Routledge), 2013.

4) Bruce Cumings. Korea's Place in the Sun: A Modern History, (New York; London: W. W. Norton), 2005.

courses.recommended_readings:
1) James Lewis and Amadu Sesay (eds.) Korea and Globalization: politics, economics and culture, (London: RoutledgeCurzon, 2002);
2) Hee-yeon Cho, Lawrence Surendra & Hyo-je Cho (eds.) Contemporary South Korean Society: a critical perspective, (Oxon: Routledge, 2013);
3) Soong Hoom Kil & Chung-in Moon (eds.), Understanding Korean Politics: an introduction, (Albany: State University of New York Press, 2001);
4) Song Jesook (ed), New Millennium South Korea: Neoliberal Capitalism and Transnational Movements. (Milton Park, Abingdon, Oxon, [England];
New York: Routledge), 2011. ;
5) Chua Beng Huat and Koichi Iwabuchi (eds), East Asian Pop Culture: Analysing the Korean Wave. (Hong Kong: Hong Kong University Press),

2008;
6) Chung-in Moon, The Sunshine Policy: In Defense of Engagement as a Path to Peace in Korea, (Seoul, Korea: Yonsei University Press, 2012);
7) Young-Chan Kim, Doo-Jin Kim and Young Jun Kim, South Korea: Challenging Globalisation and the Post-crisis Reforms, (Oxford, England:

Chandos Pub., 2008) );
8) Kyong Ju Kim, The Development of Modern South Korea: State Formation, Capitalist Development and National Identity , (Abingdon, Oxon;
New York, NY: Routledge, 2006).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the key concepts and features of Global Civil Society;
2) identify and assess the impacts of GCS and NGOs on Global Governance;
3) identify the major deficiencies of NGOs in terms of its structures and operation methods;
4) relate the concepts with other related subjects, e.g. Global Governance and International Law;
5) relate the contents with daily-life examples;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Conceptual understandings of NGOs, Non-State Actors, and Global Civil Society;
2) Globalization: NGOs, transnationalism and operations;
3) Assessments over the major themes and issues put forward in the GCS: Human Rights, Fair-Trade, Women's Right, Conservations and Gay Marriage;
4) NGOs in formulating national policies;
5) NGOs in Global Governance: Legal Personality, Rights and role;
6) Cooperation with UN: Global Compact Project;
7) Global Civil Society and "Dark Side of Non-State Actors";
8) NGOs and Global Democracy;
9) Opportunities and Challenges encountered by NGOs in the 21st century

courses.required_readings:
1) Sidney Tarrow, Power in Movement: Social Movements and Contentious Politics, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1998);
2) Charles Tilly, Contentious politics, (Colo. : Paradigm Publishers, 2007);
3) Michael Edwards, Civil Society, 2nd Edition (Cambridge: Polity, 2009).

courses.recommended_readings:
1) John Keane, Global Civil Society? (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2003);
2) Margaret Keck, Activists Beyond Borders: Advocacy Networks in International Politics, (Ithaca, N.Y. : Cornell University Press, 1998);
3) Bob Edwards, Michael W. Foley, & Mario Diani. (eds.), Beyond Tocqueville: Civil Society and the Social Capital Debate in Comparative Perspective, (Hanover, NH: University Press of New England Tufts University, 2001);
4) Paulo Freire (translated by Myra Bergman Ramos), Pedagogy of the Oppressed, (New York : Continuum, 1993).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the key concepts of E-Governance and the blurring boundaries between the virtual society and the real society;
2) identify the changing responses of different political actors towards the IT Revolution and assess their impacts to the Global Society;
3) identify the potential threats brought about from advancement of interconnectedness;
4) relate the content with the daily contexts;
5) judge the extent to which the virtual society can substitute the physical network;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Concepts and theoretical analysis of the e- words: E-politics; E-commerce; E-governance;
2) IT products in Global market: WTO, MNCs and 'patent wars';
3) Information flow and transnational political influence: E-petition in UK; Facebook and Arab Spring;
4) IT, equality and development

5) Internet and growth of online transaction: Amazon, Taobao and Bitcoins;
6) Internet and reconfiguration of identity: Virtual states, the Principality of Sealand;
7) IT for individual and society

8) Rise of Cybercrime and Cybersecurity;
9) National policies towards IT Revolution;
10) IT in Global Governance;
11) Opportunities and Challenges to "Traditional" understanding of Social Science

courses.required_readings:
1) James Slevin, The Internet and Society, (Cambridge: Polity Press, 2000);
2) Manuel Castellas, Networks of Outrage and Hope: Social movements in the Internet Age, (Cambridge: Polity Press, 2012);
3) Nick Couldry, Media, Society, World: Social Theory and Digital Media Practice, (Cambridge: Polity Press, 2012)

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Michael Mandiberg (ed.), The Social Media Reader, (New York: New York University Press, 2012);
2) Geert Lovink, Networks without a Cause: A Critique of Social Media, (Cambridge: Polity Press, 2011); 3) James Curran, Natalie Fenton & Des Freedman, Misunderstanding the Internet, (Oxon: Routledge, 2012);
4) Philip N. Howard & Muzami M. Hussain, Democracy's Fourth Wave? : Digital Media and the Arab Spring, (New York: Oxford University Press, 2013);
5) Michael E. Milakovich, Digital Governance: New Technologies for Improving Public Service and Participation, (Oxon: Routledge, 2012).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the key concepts of development studies;
2) identify the root causes of inequality in the "Third-World Countries" and how Globalization has influenced upon its spread;
3) relate this subject with other courses, e.g. World Economies, and borrow the analytical framework for providing an extra perspective;
4) relate the content with real-life contexts;
5) review critically the news media's report and politicians' rhetoric on these developing countries

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction on development studies: concepts of development and inequality;
2) Features and variants of the Developmental States;
3) Impact of Globalization (I): Modernization and Development: Asia as examples;
4) Impact of Globalization (II): Dependency and World Systems Theories;
5) Impact of Globalization (III): Colonialism and Cultural Imperialism;
6) Poverty and Gender Inequality;
7) Poverty and labour/income inequality;
8) International responses: Structural Adjustment Programs, Poverty Reduction Strategy Papers, and Millennium Development Goals;
9) South-South Cooperation;
10) Role of NGOs: Human Rights, Gender and Welfare;
11) Challenges and Possibilities in the 21st century

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Peter Alcock, Understanding Poverty, 3rd edition, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2006);
2) Peter Townsend & David Gordon (eds.), World Poverty: new policies to defeat an old enemy, (London: Polity Press, 2002);
3) Arturo Escobar, Encountering Development: The Making and Unmaking of the Third World, (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1995);
4) Damien Kingsbury et al, International Development: Issues and Challenges, 2nd edition, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2012)

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:
1) explore and develop his/her own research interests;
2) work individually and independently;
3) integrate and apply the knowledge acquired in other subjects to analyze global issues;
4) develop critical thinking and challenge the inadequacies of existing literatures;
5) present his/her own idea through verbal and written presentations

By the end of the course students should be able to:
1) explore and develop his/her own research interests;
2) work individually and independently;
3) integrate and apply the knowledge acquired in other subjects to analyze global issues;
4) develop critical thinking and challenge the inadequacies of existing literatures;
5) present his/her own idea through verbal and written presentations

By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) understand the relationships between the world religions and global changes;
2) offer empirically account of the contemporary religious movements in the global order;
3) make comparisons of several global issues from perspectives of Christian and Muslim ethics and theology

courses.course_syllabus:
1) To what extent the world religions influence the global order;
2) How did Islam and Christianity shape the economies and societies in different regions since the Second World War;
3) Some major debates about religious movements and social-economics changes;
4) Differences and similarities of Christian and Muslim ideologies to address similar social problems in the world;
5) Reflections on what it means to be human, with an interpretation of personal and common good ethics under globalization.

courses.required_readings:
1) Samuel Huntington, The Clash of Civilization and the Remaking of World Order, (New York: Simon & Schuster, 1996);
2) Charles Tripp, Islam and the Moral Economy: The Challenge of Capitalism, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2006);
3) John Atherton, Transfiguring Capitalism: An Enquiry into Religion and Global Change, (London: SCM Press, 2008).

courses.recommended_readings:
1) James Campbell, Songs of Zion: The African Methodist Episcopal Church in the United States and South Africa, (New York: Oxford University Press, 1995);
2) David Robinson, Muslim Societies in African History, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004);
3) Simon Murden, Islam, the Middle East, and the New Global Hegemony, (Colo.: Lynne Rienner Publishers, 2002);
4) Rebecca Todd Peters, In Search of the Good Life: The Ethics of Globalization., (New York : Continuum, 2004);
5) Francis Fukuyama, The Great Disruption: Human Nature and the Reconstitution of Social Order, (New York, Free Press, 1999);
6) R.H. Tawney, Religion and the Rise of Capitalism, (New Brunswick, N.J: Transaction Publishers, 1998).

courses.learning_outcomes:
1. Mastery of basic descriptive analysis;
2. Deeper understanding of the probability and inference as well as multivariate linear and non-linear regression analyses;
3. Deeper understanding on how to design, analyze and write a quantitative paper;
4. Ability to identify appropriate data sources and carry out quantitative analyses.

By the end of the course students should be able to :

1) identify the mainstream theories regarding Strategic studies and security studies and assess their usefulness in explaining the phenomenon and behaviours;
2) identify the differences/similarities between the different schools of thoughts in relation to strategic studies;
3) identify the major traditional security challenges confronted by nation-states and global governance nowadays;
4) assess the importance of traditional security challenges to us;
5) relate the content with different policies undertaken by different countries;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to strategic studies and security studies;
2) Overview of Military Technology and Strategic thinking of the Major Powers: Air, Land and Sea Power ;
3) Strategic Studies from the East: Sun Tsz and others;
4) Strategic Studies from the West: Clausewitz and others;
5) IR Theories and Strategic Studies;
6) Theories and Practices of Conflict Resolution;
7) History of War;
8) Perception and the Threat of Force: Nuclear Deterrence and WMD;
9) Alliance System;
10) Individuals, Regional Security Institutions, the United Nations Security Council in peacekeeping;
11) Democracy and Peace;
12) Assessment of the level of threats imposed by "Traditional" Security Threats under Globalization: Opportunities and Challenges

courses.required_readings:
1) Thomas G. Mahnken & Joseph A. Maiolo (eds.), Strategic Studies: A Reader, (Oxon: Routledge, 2008);
2) John Baylis, James J. Wirtz & Colin S. Gray (eds.), Strategy in the Contemporary World, 3rd edition, (London: Oxford University Press, 2010);
3) Paul D. Williams (ed.), Security Studies: An Introduction, 2nd edition, (Oxon: Routledge, 2012).

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Colin S. Gray, Modern Strategy, (Oxon: Oxford University Press, 1999);
2) David Jordan & James D. Kiras (eds.), Understanding Modern Warfare, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2008);
3) Michael E. Brown, et al(eds.), Theories of War and Peace, (Cambridge: MIT Press; 1998);
4) Bradley S. Klein, Strategic Studies and World Order; The Global Politics of Deterrence, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1994);
5) Carl von Clausewitz, On War, (Oxford: Oxford University Press), 2007;
6) Sun Tzu, The Art of War, (New York: Cosmio, 2006);
7) Peter Wallensteen, Understanding Conflict Resolution: War, Peace and the Global System, 3rd edition, (London: SAGE Publications, 2011);
8) Hew Strachan & Andreas Herberg-Rothe (eds.), Clausewitz in the Twenty-first Century, (Oxon: Oxford University Press, 2007).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the new security challenges imposed;
2) identify the role of different actors in addressing such challenges;
3) refer the content with the daily contexts;
4) refer the content with different topics come across in other courses, e.g. Theories of Military, War and Peace, and compare the judgments by different scholars;
5) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to New Security Challenges: Non-Traditional Security and Human Security;
2) International Relations Theories and New Security Challenges: How valid and useful are they?

3) New and Old Wars;
4) Terrorism and Insurgencies;
5) Power of Nightmares: Islamic Fundamentalism vs. Neo-Conservatism;
6) Unrestricted Warfare: Terrorism from China's Perspective;
7) Private Security Companies and Mercenaries;
8) Drug Trafficking;
9) Maritime Privacy;
10) Cross-Border Prostitution;
11) National, Regional, Global Response towards New Security Challenges;
12) Comparison with the "Traditional" Security Threats

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Gus Martin, Understanding Terrorism: Challenges, Perspectives, and Issues, 4th edition, (London: SAGE Publications, 2013);
2) Bruce Hoffman, Inside Terrorism, 2nd edition, (New York: Columbia University Press, 2006);
3) Craig A. Synder (ed.), Contemporary Security and Strategy, 3rd edition, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2011);
4) Paul D. Williams (ed.), Security Studies: An Introduction, , 2nd edition, (Oxon: Routledge, 2012);
5) Mary Kaldor, Human Security: Reflections on Globalization and Intervention, (Cambridge: Polity Press, 2007).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) describe major concepts in the topics related to urbanization and political space use;
2) apply the concepts to illustrate their everyday life in a global city and to bring personal reflections on a

current issue in mass consumption;
3) use a specific theoretical perspective acquired in GLBS3105 to analyze a collective behavior in the city

in their written assignments or group projects.

By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the logic and governance of global capital flow;
2) identify the impact of global capital flow on domestic and international markets, not least on the property market;
3) identify and assess the role of different actors in governing the financial systems;
4) refer the content with different topics come across in other courses, e.g. World Economies, and compare the analysis;
5) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to Financial Globalization: Basic concepts of Global Capital Flows, FDI, Interest Rate, Exchange Rate;
2) Actors in Global Financial Markets (I): MNCs and Credit Agencies;
3) Actors in Global Financial Markets (II): Central Banks;
4) Actors in Global Financial Markets (III): Bank of International Settlement;
5) Actors in Global Financial Markets (IV): the Bretton Wood Institutions and Inter-Governmental Organizations;
6) Overview of the Financial Markets and various products: Derivatives, FXs, Bonds and Stocks;
7) FDI and Development: China as an example;
8) Currency War and Global Capital Flows: Japan as an Example;
9) Global Capital Flows and Financial Crimes: the case of Money Laundering and Offshore tax haven; 10) Property Markets and Global Capital Flows: the Subprime Mortgage Crisis as case studies

courses.required_readings:
1) George Cooper, The Origin of Financial Crises, (New York: Random House, 2008);
2) Andrew Baker, David Hudson & Richard Woodward (eds.), Governing Financial Globalization : international political economy and multi-level governance, (Oxon: Routledge, 2005);
3) Stephen Valdez & Philip Molyneux, An Introduction to Global Financial Markets, 6th edition, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2010)

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Jeffry A. Frieden, Global Capitalism: Its Fall and Rise in the Twentieth Century, (New York: W.W. Norton & Company, 2007);
2) John Ravenhill, Global Political Economy, 3rd edition, (New York: Oxford University Press, 2011);
3) Randall Germain, Global Politics & Financial Governance, (Basingstoke: Palgrave Macmillan, 2010);
4) Eric Hellener, States and the Reemergence of Global Finance: From Bretton Woods to the 1990s, (Ithaca, Cornell University Press, 1994);
5) Timothy J. Sinclair & Lena Rethel, The Problem with Banks, (New York: Zed Books, 2012).

courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course students should be able to:

1) identify the strategies and balancing moves adopted by China regarding the Global economic and financial market;
2) identify the major issues in China's bid for great power status in the Global Economy;
3) primary opportunities and challenges encountered by China's internationalization;
4) refer the content with daily examples;
5) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) China's in the Global political economy since 1978;
2) China's reform strategies, developmental model and internationalization programs;
3) Internationalization of Chinese urban cities and Special Economic Zones;
4) Internationalization of Chinese rural economy;
5) Internationalization of Human Capital in China - the Brain Drain Effect;
6) China's FDI in the World;
7) China's Sovereign Wealth Fund and operations;
8) China and Hong Kong, and RMB Internationalization;
9) China and Free Trade Agreements;
10) China's accession to WTO;
11) China's role in IMF and the Idea of Supranational Currency

